{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":0.8,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Data completeness is variable across regions and indicators, with antenatal care, delivery by skilled birth attendant, BCG, Penta1 and Penta 3 vaccination, and outpatient services, reporting above 90% completeness across most regions. 

Several indicators, including PNC visit for mothers and newborns, delivery by caesarian section, malaria treated with ACT, fever cases tested for malaria (microscopy and RDT), and children diagnosed with SAM often fall below 80%, which may affect reliability for those services.

Weaker reporting in Benadir, Gedo, Middle Shebelle, Lower Juba, and Ayn regions suggests the need for targeted improvements in regional reporting."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.6,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"b64d2c67-35c5-413b-a035-c425cf9ce243","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Reporting completeness"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1: Consistently below expectations in 2025, averaging ~64,200 vs. ~71,100 expected (~10% lower). July 2025 was ~66,300 (~10% lower).

ANC4: Stayed close to expected, averaging ~21,700 vs. ~22,400 expected (~3% lower). July 2025 was ~22,100 (~5% lower).

 ANC1 shows persistent shortfalls, and fewer women continue to ANC4, underscoring a continuity gap in antenatal care. Overall, both indicators align closely with expectations, but ANC1 shows a higher persistent shortfall compared to expected service use."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f13bc674-ef5d-4619-9723-9bf804e56ee5","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Antenatal Care Service Use Similar to Expected Trends"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, the overall DQA score declined slightly from 75% in 2022 to 71% in 2025.

Several regions achieved strong results above 85% in 2025, including Karkaar, Mudug (Puntland), Nugaal, Sanaag, Sool, Bakool, and Bay. 

However, data quality has declined in many areas, with Benadir, Hiiraan, Middle Shebelle, Lower Juba, Ayn and Ras-Asayr falling below 65%. These regions show the greatest need for renewed support to strengthen reporting completeness as of 2025."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"3d0f3ecc-b1e8-4cd3-b2dd-55b0823e65ae","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, outliers remain low, with nearly all indicators averaging below 3%, suggesting consistency in reporting quality across most services.

Outliers are slightly higher for a few indicators, particularly for Penta1 & Penta3 vaccination and outpatient visits.

Reporting is stable across most regions, though Benadir, Hiiraan, Ras-Asayr, and Lower Shabelle show higher variability across several indicators, suggesting localized reporting challenges rather than systemwide issues."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.6,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"e4c3a72a-fc9b-49ee-975e-f9de03cde153","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Outliers"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgFile":"6862512746_5eb2f85757_o.jpg","imgFit":"cover","markdown":"","imgStretch":true,"imgHeight":250},{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"primary","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"markdown":"L’approche FASTR utilise les données de routine du DHIS2 pour suivre l’évolution de la prestation des services dans le temps.

En comparant les volumes de services observés et attendus — ajustés en fonction de la saisonnalité et des tendances historiques — nous pouvons identifier les perturbations ou les excédents dans les services de santé essentiels.

Cette analyse fournit une perspective globale et opportune, mettant en évidence où et quand l’utilisation des services s’écarte des tendances attendues. Les résultats produisent des données exploitables pour orienter des réponses rapides et contribuer à maintenir la continuité des soins essentiels en période d’incertitude de financement ou de changements opérationnels."}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Suivi des perturbations dans les services essentiels à l’aide des données du DHIS2","useFooter":false,"footerLogos":[]}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Les consultations postnatales dans la première semaine (SPN1) pour les nouveaux-nés se maintiennent de façon assez régulière autour de 40 000 à 45 000 visites mensuelles. Depuis mi-2025, un excédent de +10 à +12 % apparaît, indiquant une amélioration de la couverture.

Pour les mères, la tendance est similaire : après une stabilité proche de 40 000 visites, on observe également un surplus marqué en 2025 (+8 à +10 %).

"},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"2804d933-de71-41bc-8594-ca1dda00a640","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"SPN1 nouveau-né et mères en excédent récent après une période stable"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"CPN1 : Les volumes sont restés globalement stables autour de 65 000–70 000 contacts mensuels, avec un léger excédent mi-2025 (+5 à +8 %).

CPN4 : En revanche, une forte baisse persistante est observée depuis fin 2023, les volumes chutant de près de 50 000 à environ 30 000, soit un déficit soutenu de 20–30 %.

CPN1 précoce (<16 semaines) : Bien que les niveaux absolus restent inférieurs à ceux du CPN1 total, une tendance positive est visible depuis fin 2024, avec quelques excédents, suggérant une légère amélioration de l’initiation précoce."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"24810455-def0-474f-9e3f-2efc9c572490","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Les CPN1 restent stables, l’initiation avant 16 semaines s’améliore, mais les CPN4 affichent un déficit persistant"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 volumes rose through 2024 before dipping in early 2025 and returning to around 70,000 visits by mid-year.

ANC4 showed stable but lower volumes, averaging ~20,000 visits monthly since 2023, with a slight increase over time.

