{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"Postnatal care for newborns fluctuated through 2023 and 2024 before rising more sharply in early 2025, nearing 21,000 visits by mid-2025, reflecting stronger uptake of early postnatal follow-up for newborns.

Postnatal care for mothers remained consistently higher across the period, with modest variation and a gradual increase through 2025 to about 29,000 visits, suggesting sustained service use but slower growth relative to newborn follow-up.

Addressing the gap between newborn and maternal postnatal visits remains important to ensure both are reached consistently and continuity of care is maintained across the postnatal period."},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"dd7772cf-8e1e-4eda-926a-3a5bd9dd5b20","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in postnatal care"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"BCG volumes fluctuated through the period, with small gains in 2023 and mid-2024 followed by a decline in early 2025, returning to ~50,000 doses by mid-2025.

Penta1 and Penta3 followed broadly similar trends, with noticeable parallel rises and dips through 2024 and early 2025. By mid-2025, Penta1 reached ~64,000 doses, while Penta3 was ~57,000, indicating an estimated 11% dropout between the first and third doses.

Overall, immunization volumes dipped across all vaccines in early 2025, suggesting possible service disruptions. Addressing the gap between Penta1 and Penta3 remains important to ensure full protection."},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"62ce52f6-b5ef-4a90-b7b8-6f1be328aec1","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in child immunization"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Across regions, consistency remains strong overall. 

Nationally, ANC1 vs. ANC4 consistency is very high (100%), with all regions meeting the benchmark. However, Penta1 vs. Penta3 consistency is weaker, averaging 94% and dropping as low as 75% in Mudug (Galmudug) and Hiiraan regions, underscoring where data plausibility checks are most critical.

"},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"94f96848-5e34-425b-a09e-79ec325393ed","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Internal consistency"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"PNC1 for newborns shows persistent disruptions, averaging about 20% below expected levels, with July 2025 nearly 22% lower than expected.

PNC1 for mothers also falls below expectations, averaging about 11% lower, with July 2025 around 13% lower, similarly reflecting incomplete reporting.

Across both indicators, the shaded shortfalls reflect a mix of service use and reporting disruptions, and the pattern appears to be driven largely by reporting completeness issues rather than true declines in postnatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"413db1fe-09e8-4b5e-b3d6-6316dc783df0","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Postnatal care shortfalls likely reporting-driven, with larger gaps for newborns"}}

